## 2. Chat / File Relationship

| Question | Decision |
|---|---|
| Files per chat | **One active file per chat session** |
| File-chat link | `fileId` stored on the **Chat MongoDB document** (new field) |
| Multiple files later | Supported by design — `Chat.fileId` can evolve to `Chat.fileIds[]` |
| File upload scope | File is uploaded **globally to Pinecone** under the user's namespace, then linked to a specific chat via `fileId` |

**Why file linked to chat:**
- User opens Chat A with `contract.pdf` active → asks questions → AI uses that file
- User opens Chat B → no file linked → pure LLM chat
- Switching chats switches file context automatically (no stale file bleeds across chats)

---

## 3. Active File Context — Refresh Restoration

| Scenario | Behavior |
|---|---|
| Page refresh | File context is **restored from the backend** — the `Chat` document stores `fileId + fileName` |
| Opening a chat | `getMessages` API response will include `fileContext: { fileId, fileName, status }` |
| Logout | Frontend file state clears; **Pinecone vectors persist** (user owns them) |
| Login again | File context restores correctly when user reopens the linked chat |

**Implementation:**
- `Chat` model gains `fileId` (String) and `fileName` (String) optional fields
- `getMessages` endpoint returns these fields in response
- Frontend reads them and re-hydrates Redux `fileContext` state on chat open

---

## 4. Retrieval Defaults

| Parameter | Value | Reasoning |
|---|---|---|
| Chunk size | **1000 characters** | ~250 tokens — fits comfortably in context without truncation |
| Chunk overlap | **150 characters** | Prevents sentence splitting on boundaries |
| Top-K retrieval | **5 chunks** | Enough context without bloating the LLM prompt |
| Minimum similarity score | **0.72** | Below this = chunk is not relevant enough; discard |
| Max context chars fed to LLM | **4000 chars** (5 chunks × 800 avg) | Safe within Gemini context window |

**Fallback rule:** If 0 chunks meet the 0.72 threshold → respond with a specific message (see Section 8).

---

## 5. File Metadata — MongoDB Storage

A new `FileUpload` Mongoose model will be created:

```js
{
  fileId: String,         // uuid v4, unique
  userId: ObjectId,       // ref: User
  chatId: ObjectId,       // ref: Chat (which chat this is linked to)
  fileName: String,       // original file name e.g. "contract.pdf"
  fileSize: Number,       // bytes
  pageCount: Number,      // extracted from pdf-parse
  chunkCount: Number,     // total chunks stored in Pinecone
  namespace: String,      // "user-{userId}"
  status: String,         // 'uploading' | 'parsing' | 'embedding' | 'indexing' | 'ready' | 'failed'
  errorMessage: String,   // populated on 'failed'
  uploadedAt: Date,
  updatedAt: Date
}
```

This gives you a full audit trail and enables a status polling endpoint (`GET /api/files/:fileId/status`).

---

## 6. File Lifecycle Rules

| Scenario | Behavior |
|---|---|
| Delete chat | Pinecone vectors for linked file are **also deleted** automatically |
| User clicks "Remove file" | Pinecone vectors deleted + `FileUpload` doc deleted + `Chat.fileId` cleared |
| Re-upload same file | New `fileId` is generated; old vectors remain until explicitly deleted |
| Logout | Pinecone vectors **persist** (user's data is preserved across sessions) |
| User deletion | Future: cascade delete all user namespaces |

---

## 7. Indexing States — Full State Machine

```
[uploading]  →  File received by backend via multer
[parsing]    →  pdf-parse extracting text
[embedding]  →  Mistral generating vectors for all chunks
[indexing]   →  Pinecone upsert in progress
[ready]      →  All done, file available for RAG queries
[failed]     →  Any step above failed; errorMessage populated
```

**Frontend shows:**
- `uploading` → spinner + "Uploading file..."
- `parsing` → spinner + "Reading document..."
- `embedding` → spinner + "Analyzing content..."
- `indexing` → spinner + "Indexing document..."
- `ready` → green badge + "📄 filename.pdf · Ready"
- `failed` → red badge + error message + retry option

**State delivery:** Backend processes synchronously in one request (no polling for now). Final state (`ready` or `failed`) returned in the upload API response. Status endpoint available for future async upgrade.

---

## 8. Fallback Behavior — No Relevant Chunks

When `fileId` is present but no chunks score above **0.72**, the response will be:

> *"I couldn't find relevant information about that in the uploaded document **[filename]**. The document may not contain details on this topic, or try rephrasing your question."*

When classifier routes to `GENERAL` (unrelated question despite active file):

> Normal LLM response — no mention of the file, no Pinecone query.

---

## 9. Multi-File Future Design

The current architecture is **designed to support multiple files** with zero refactor:

- `Chat.fileId` → can become `Chat.fileIds: [String]`  
- Pinecone query filter → `{ userId, fileId: { $in: [id1, id2] } }`
- Classifier → returns which file(s) the question is about
- Only the retrieval filter needs updating — all services stay the same

---

## 10. Access Control

| Layer | Rule |
|---|---|
| Pinecone namespace | `user-{userId}` — users only query their own namespace |
| Metadata filter | Every query additionally filters `{ fileId: X, userId: Y }` as double-check |
| Upload endpoint | `authenticate` middleware required — `userId` comes from `req.user.id` |
| Delete endpoint | Validates that `FileUpload.userId === req.user.id` before deleting |
| Status endpoint | Validates ownership before returning file status |

---

## 11. Corrupt / Empty PDF Handling

| Case | Response |
|---|---|
| File not PDF (wrong MIME) | `400 Bad Request` — "Only PDF files are accepted" |
| File >10MB | `400 Bad Request` — "File size must be under 10MB" |
| PDF parses but text is empty | `422 Unprocessable Entity` — "This PDF appears to be empty or image-only (scanned). Text extraction is not supported for image PDFs." |
| PDF is corrupt / unreadable | `422 Unprocessable Entity` — "The uploaded PDF could not be read. Please ensure it is a valid, uncorrupted PDF file." |
| Embedding API failure | `502 Bad Gateway` — "Failed to generate embeddings. Please try again." + `FileUpload.status = 'failed'` |
| Pinecone upsert failure | `502 Bad Gateway` — "Failed to store document index. Please try again." + cleanup attempted |

**Cleanup flow on failure:** If any step fails, `FileUpload` doc is updated to `status: 'failed'` with `errorMessage`. No orphaned vectors remain since upsert only happens after all embeddings succeed.

